Here's how to implement all three requirements:

## 1. Custom "Cancel" Back Button on `EditProductPage`

In your page XAML, override `BackButtonBehavior`:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

## 2. ViewModel with Unsaved-Changes Guard

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    async Task Cancel()
    {
        if (await ConfirmDiscard())
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }

    public async Task<bool> ConfirmDiscard()
    {
        if (!HasUnsavedChanges)
            return true;

        return await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard your changes?",
            "Discard", "Stay");
    }
}
```

## 3. Guard the System Back (Swipe / Hardware Button)

Override `OnNavigating` in `AppShell.xaml.cs` to catch back gestures that bypass the custom button:

```csharp
public partial class AppShell : Shell
{
    public AppShell()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        Routing.RegisterRoute("editproduct", typeof(EditProductPage));
    }

    protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
    {
        base.OnNavigating(args);

        // Only intercept back navigation ("Pop")
        if (args.Source != ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
            return;

        // Only guard the EditProductPage
        if (CurrentPage is not EditProductPage page)
            return;

        if (page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
            && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            // Pause navigation for the async dialog
            var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

            bool discard = await vm.ConfirmDiscard();
            if (!discard)
                args.Cancel();   // user chose "Stay"

            deferral.Complete(); // resume or cancel
        }
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- `GetDeferral()` is required because `DisplayAlert` is async; without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- `args.Cancel()` stops the navigation entirely.
- `deferral.Complete()` must always be called — it either finalizes the cancellation or lets navigation proceed.
- The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the toolbar button; `OnNavigating` handles swipe-back and the Android hardware back button.
